    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! During Anaphase, the sister chromatids, which were previously joined at the centromere, are pulled apart by the spindle fibers. These fibers, attached to the kinetochores of each chromatid, shorten and pull the chromatids toward opposite poles of the cell. This ensures that each new daughter cell will receive an identical set of chromosomes.\n\nFollowing Anaphase, the cell enters Telophase. In this stage, the separated chromatids, now individual chromosomes, reach the poles of the cell. A new nuclear envelope begins to form around each set of chromosomes, creating two distinct nuclei within the cell. The chromosomes start to decondense, returning to their less tightly coiled state. Finally, the spindle fibers disassemble, and the cell prepares to complete its division through cytokinesis, which will physically separate the cytoplasm into two new cells.",
      "source": "target",
