      "content": "The spindle fibers pull the sister chromatids apart through a precise mechanism involving the kinetochore, a protein structure on the centromere of each chromatid. During Anaphase, the kinetochore binds to the spindle fibers, and as the microtubules shorten, they exert a pulling force on the kinetochores, which are anchored to the chromatids.\n\nThis pulling is facilitated by motor proteins called dyneins and kinesins that \"walk\" along the microtubules. These motor proteins use ATP, the energy currency of the cell, to move the spindle fibers and generate the force needed to separate the chromatids. The microtubules are dynamic structures that can grow and shrink, allowing them to pull the chromatids apart with great precision.\n\nThe cell also has a checkpoint system that ensures the chromatids are properly attached to the spindle fibers before separation occurs. This checkpoint prevents the cell from dividing until all chromosomes are correctly aligned and attached, reducing the chance of errors in chromosome segregation.",
